Urbanization and spiders

Background

We will be examining data from: Dahirel et al.2019. Urbanization-driven changes in web building and body size in an orb web spider. Journal of Animal Ecology. 88:79-91. Here are links to the paper and data.

Note: I would encourage you to check out the format with which they provided their data and code. These authors did a particularly good job as they provided data, code and metadata (this is not as common as Id like - now that Im scrounging Dryad for datasets for our class.) These authors store their data in a way that I encourage, which is multiple files for different types of data that can be joined through tidying data before analysis. So this is a great example! I also fully realize you could look at their code and use it to inform your homework answers, but I encourage you to challenge yourself and try it without looking at the code and instead working in your groups. I wont be asking you for the exact same analyses they do in their paper, so try to answer the homework questions without looking, and then check out their code later (its beatifully commented).

In this paper, the authors examine orb weaver spiders (check them out here) and how their body size and web building changes with urbanization. Orb weaver spiders are particularly interesting because their behavior can be understood by measuring their webs characteristics. For example, when spiders experience low prey capture, they will increase the capture area of their web to make sure they catch something. Alternatively, they will build smaller webs with finer structure to maximize prey retention when prey density is high. So tracking web size and construction can allow for an understanding of the resource availability a spider is facing. We will be using their data to practice mixed effects models that follow both normal and non-normal distributions.

Posthoc Pairwise Comparisons

Even though we know that local urbanization affects web surface area because our Anova() summary of our model tells us its significant, we dont know which treatments are actually different from each other. So we must do post-hoc comparisons. There are two ways to do this. 1) with emmeans() in the library(emmeans) and 2) with glht() in the library(multcomp).

Q8 Try both posthoc methods and determine which treatments are producing signficantly different web surface area relative to each other. You will need to either read the emmeans() documentation, the glht() documentation, or this helpful website. What did you find?

#  method 1 using emmeans()

emmeans(mod_7_b, pairwise ~ local_urban)

Q11 Based on our analyses here, what can you conclude about Naraneus spiders and urbanization?

# The number of Naraneus spiders does not differ at any level
#   of urbanization. However, when considering urbanization at
#   the local scale, we see smaller spiders in areas of higher 
#   local urbanization, and we see larger webs at small urbanization
#   as compared to large urbanization. This means in general, that
#   spiders are trying to maximize prey caught in local low
#   urban environments, but are trying to maximize prey caught
#   in high urban environments (perhaps because the spiders are
#   smaller, they need to maximize prey to make sure they have
#   enough resources.)
